Indications:
Avoid strongly impacting to the oximeter.
Avoid the oximeter to be exposed straight to the Daylight.
Do not charge the battery for more than 5 hours, or which will cause damage to the battery.
Charging is not recommended when using the Oximeter.
Do not charge or preserve the battery in too hot or cold environment.
Benefits:
Observing oxygen saturation over time
Alerting to risky low oxygen levels, Especially in new-borns.
Evaluating the need for supplemental oxygen
Monitoring oxygen saturation levels in people under anaesthesia
Directions:
Remove the back cap and insert the batteries.
Insert your finger into the pulse oximeter and wait for the unit to power on.
The number on the left is the SpO2 which indicates the oxygen saturation of your blood.
The number on the right is the pulse rate which indicate how many times per minute your heart beats.
The waveform at the bottom offers a visual reference of your heartbeat.
Features:
OLED Display
SpO2 Measuring Range: 0%-100% (Resolution of 1%)
Power consumption: less than 25mA
Voltage: DC2.6V-3.6V
